   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Mean Squared Error"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "8278e264",
   "metadata": {
    "vscode": {
     "languageId": "raw"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "Mean Squared Error (MSE) is a common metric used to evaluate the accuracy of a model by measuring the average of the squares of the errors—that is, the average squared difference between the estimated values and the actual value.\n",
    "\n",
    "Advantages:\n",
    "\n",
    "MSE penalizes larger errors more heavily due to squaring, making it sensitive to outliers.\n",
    "It is differentiable, which makes it suitable for optimization algorithms like gradient descent.\n",
    "It provides a clear, interpretable measure of model performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "Disadvantages:\n",
    "\n",
    "MSE is in squared units, which can make it difficult to interpret in the context of the original data.\n",
    "It is sensitive to outliers, which can skew the error metric.\n",
    "MSE may not be the best choice when the data contains many extreme values or when the cost of large errors is not proportionally high."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8eca8e3d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Mean Absolute Error"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "5b5f47b3",
   "metadata": {
    "vscode": {
     "languageId": "raw"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "Mean Absolute Error (MAE) measures the average of the absolute differences between predicted and actual values — it’s the mean of the absolute errors.\n",
    "\n",
    "Advantages:\n",
    "\n",
    "MAE is easy to interpret since it’s in the same units as the target variable.\n",
    "It’s robust to outliers because it doesn’t square the errors.\n",
    "It provides a straightforward measure of average error magnitude.\n",
    "\n",
    "Disadvantages:\n",
    "\n",
    "MAE is not differentiable at zero, which can complicate optimization.\n",
    "It treats all errors equally, so it doesn’t penalize large errors as heavily as MSE.\n",
    "Less sensitive to model improvements when large errors dominate the error profile."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4d4c2c04",
   "metadata": {
    "vscode": {
     "languageId": "raw"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "## Root Mean Squared Error"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "72d26d62",
   "metadata": {
    "vscode": {
     "languageId": "raw"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) is the square root of the Mean Squared Error (MSE). It measures the standard deviation of the residuals (prediction errors), giving a sense of how spread out these errors are.\n",
    "\n",
    "Advantages:\n",
    "\n",
    "RMSE is in the same units as the target variable, making it more interpretable than MSE.\n",
    "It penalizes larger errors more than MAE, which can be useful when large errors are particularly undesirable.\n",
    "It’s widely used and understood in many fields, especially in regression modeling.\n",
    "\n",
    "Disadvantages:\n",
    "\n",
    "Like MSE, RMSE is sensitive to outliers due to the squaring step.\n",
    "It’s not as intuitive as MAE for non-technical audiences.\n",
    "It can be misleading if the error distribution is skewed or contains extreme values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "4621701e",
   "metadata": {
    "vscode": {
     "languageId": "raw"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "When to Use Which:\n",
    "Use MAE → When you want a simple, intuitive error metric and outliers shouldn’t dominate your evaluation.\n",
    "Use MSE → When you’re optimizing a model (e.g., via gradient descent) and care more about penalizing large errors.\n",
    "Use RMSE → When you want the interpretability of MAE plus the sensitivity to large errors — most common in reporting model performance.\n",
    "💡 Rule of thumb: If your data has many outliers → prefer MAE. If large errors are costly → prefer RMSE. If you’re training a model → MSE is often used internally for optimization."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "1b9d62f6",
   "metadata": {
    "vscode": {
     "languageId": "raw"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "Penalizing large errors means giving more weight (or “punishment”) to bigger mistakes in your model’s predictions — so a prediction that’s way off hurts your score more than one that’s slightly off.\n",
    "\n",
    "How it’s done:\n",
    "MSE & RMSE square the errors before averaging them:\n",
    "→ A small error (e.g., 2) becomes 4\n",
    "→ A large error (e.g., 10) becomes 100 — 25x worse than the small one!\n",
    "→ This makes the metric sensitive to outliers.\n",
    "\n",
    "MAE just takes the absolute value:\n",
    "→ Error of 2 → 2\n",
    "→ Error of 10 → 10 — only 5x worse\n",
    "→ So it treats all errors more evenly.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why it matters:\n",
    "If being very wrong is much worse than being a little wrong (e.g., predicting house prices or medical outcomes), use RMSE/MSE.\n",
    "If all errors are equally bad, use MAE.\n",
    "\n",
    "Short version: Squaring = penalizing big errors harder."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c9d4a619",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Formula"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "31734032",
   "metadata": {
    "vscode": {
     "languageId": "raw"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "MAE = (1/n) * Σ|yᵢ - ŷᵢ|\n",
    "\n",
    "MSE = (1/n) * Σ(yᵢ - ŷᵢ)²\n",
    "\n",
    "RMSE = √MSE = √[(1/n) * Σ(yᵢ - ŷᵢ)²]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "n = number of data points\n",
    "yᵢ = actual value\n",
    "ŷᵢ = predicted value\n",
    "Σ = sum over all data points"
   ]
  }
 ],
